Here at Auchingarrich we care for many native breeds including Hebridean Sheep. Hebridean sheep are a primitive breed often used to manage delicate ecosystems. For the past two years, we have patiently waited and prayed for the blessing of a solar system at Snehan Home. We reached out to many donors, but our efforts bore fruit only when we connected with Mr. Jay from USA.
As a grassroots NGO serving the most marginalized and neglected individuals in society, we often struggle to meet even basic daily needs. On top of this, the burden of paying â‚¹9,000â€“â‚¹10,000 every month for electricity was a constant challenge. With these pressing needs, our appeal was graciously accepted by VRIT Tech Inc, and today Snehan Home proudly has its own solar system.
This on-grid system is expected to reduce our electricity expenses to a minimum and, according to the company, has a lifespan of up to 20 years.
We take this moment to express our heartfelt gratitude to VRIT Tech Inc and to Mr. Jayâ€™s family for their valuable support. Their generosity has lightened and strengthened our mission. We assure you that Snehan will continue to reach out to the unreached, restoring dignity and hope to those who need it most. We also take this opportunity to thank Mr.Mukesh Jain for connecting us with Mr.Jay.

Snehan â€“ Goodwill Mission was honored to host the 2nd-year MSW students from Mangalore University at Snehan Home in Puducherry. A group of 42 students, accompanied by two faculty guides, visited us to gain firsthand understanding of how a grassroots-level organization is built and sustained.
The purpose of their visit was to explore Snehanâ€™s journeyâ€”why it was founded, the challenges that shaped it, how it benefits both beneficiaries and society, and the systems we use to manage funds and comply with legal frameworks.
Snehanâ€™s Director, Mr. Anumuthu (Joshi), shared his deeply personal story of leaving behind comfort and security to serve the helpless. He spoke about his early life, where poverty deprived him of education and basic child rights, and how those struggles inspired his mission to uplift others facing similar hardships.
In his pursuit, he gave up his job and earnings, even living as a beggar, to stand alongside those dying on the streets. With immense difficulty but unwavering faith, and with the support of God and well-wishers, he built Snehan into a home of dignity and hope. Today, despite limited financial resources, Snehan saves nearly 50 lives every year. As Mr. Anumuthu expressed, â€œIf only I had a little more support, many more lives could be saved.â€
His 45-minute talk left the students deeply inspired and motivated. They asked thoughtful questions, which he answered with honesty and wisdom drawn from lived experience. Snehan Home extends its heartfelt wishes to these young social change-makers as they carry forward the spirit of compassion and transformation.

What began as a small spark in Anumuthuâ€™s heart has now grown into a bright flame â€” Snehan Tailoring proudly celebrates its 8th anniversary. "Every act of charity begins within a person before it takes shape in the world".
As a little boy, Anumuthu faced the harshest realities of life. After losing his father, poverty crippled his childhood. Hunger, deprivation, and the pain of being without even basic necessities marked his tender years. Yet, by a miracle, he was lifted out of misery and given the chance to grow up like any other child by Rev.Joe Arimpoor SDB.
Those struggles left a lasting mark. He never wanted to forget what he endured, and from that memory grew a deep compassion for the less fortunate. His dream was to bring dignity and value to those who felt helpless and overlooked. That dream came alive â€” today, Snehanâ€™s social initiatives bring meaning and hope to many underprivileged lives in Puducherry.
On this special occasion, we offered prayers for Snehan Tailoring in its new space, joined by friends and tailors. Our staff were honored for their dedication, treated to a special lunch, and enjoyed a short outing together.
Snehan Tailoring stands tall as a pillar of our social work. Without this unit, Snehan Home would face immense challenges. It sustains our mission of saving lives and restoring dignity.
We take this moment to express heartfelt gratitude to all our tailors and benefactors. Your support keeps our dream alive and helps us continue to stand with those who need us most.

I took my handmade micro rod to Shenandoah National Park! After a burst of inspiration, I decided to make a custom microfishing rod and compare it to some real brookies! And what better place to go than the Blue Ridge Mountains! I think the rod turned out pretty good, but it doesn't hold a candle to the real thing! Fishing aside, the overlooks were breathtaking, and Im so thankful to have shared the experience with some great friends! Cherish these wild lands and the people who stick by you, for these are the things that truly matter!

The mountains rise with monumental clarity, their rugged slopes shaped by centuries of wind, ice, and geological upheaval. Sunlight glides across granite faces and snow-covered ridges, revealing textures that echo the timeless craftsmanship of nature. In these vast national parks, the landscape appears both ancient and ever-renewing, a testament to the enduring power that defines the American wilderness.

As daylight shifts, shadows stretch across the valleys and high basins, carving depth into the terrain and unveiling the delicate interplay between light and form. Sharp contrasts accentuate the raw geometry of the peaks, while subtle tones soften the open expanses below. Each moment of illumination becomes part of a quiet dialogue, an expression of solitude, grandeur, and the unspoken rhythms that animate these protected lands.

In black and white, the scene sheds all distraction, distilling the wilderness to its essential spirit. The mountains become more than a backdrop; they emerge as profound presences, serene yet commanding. Within this vast stillness, the viewer is invited to pause, breathe, and engage with the pure, unadorned beauty that has defined Americaâ€™s national parks for generations.

Hereâ€™s the advice Iâ€™d give me younger self ğŸ‘‡

Simplify Complex Forms: The biggest mistake I made was overcomplicating anatomy. Every part of the body can be simplified into a few simple shapes. Itâ€™s so much easier to replicate a singular shape compared to a really complex area that you donâ€™t understand.

Seek Feedback: In order to level up your art you need another set of eyes. Join a community that gives good feedback and ask for feedback on your work throughout every stage of the process.

Listen to Criticism: The biggest part of receiving feedback is actually listening to it and applying it. Even if it wasnâ€™t given in the nicest/most respectful way.

Stick with It: In order to improve you gotta have consistency, dedication, and patience. You need to commit, lock in, and stick with it for a minimum of 6 months. At that 6 month mark youâ€™ll just want to continue.

Practice and Study as much as Possible: This should go without saying, but just watching tutorials isnâ€™t enough to become an outstanding 3D artist. Thatâ€™s where most aspiring artists fail and lose hope, because of inaction.

The idea for the series came out of the chaos of a 1.5-year long home renovation and all the encounters with builders along the way.

DESIGN SELLS

Did you know that eighty five percent of consumers make their purchasing decisions by design, and one hundred percent of car purchases are driven by design.
Design is the most powerful tool for increasing sales, shaping perception, and defining value.
It is not just the product, it is the experience, the aura, the emotion.

Design is now the invisible hand guiding our choices across every part of life.
Services use design to choreograph behavior and emotion.
Think of how the layout of an app, the tone of a voice interface, or the uniform of a hotel staff member creates a feeling of trust, ease, and desire.
Design defines how we move through an airport, how we interact with a website, how we sense the quality of care in a hospital or a bank.

In industry, design separates the ordinary from the extraordinary.
Two objects with identical function can hold completely different value depending on their form, texture, and message.
Design turns utility into desire, efficiency into emotion, technology into humanity.

In real estate, design creates lifestyle.
Architecture, interiors, light, and material form an identity that commands higher value.
People no longer buy square meters, they buy atmosphere, energy, and story.
A well designed building is a brand, not a structure.

Even in politics, design has become a language of persuasion.
Campaign graphics, stage sets, typography, clothing, even gestures, all engineered to project identity, empathy, and vision.
Good design does not just communicate, it convinces.

Design sells because it seduces.
It is the fusion of beauty, utility, and meaning.
Every form we create, every space we inhabit, every object we touch shapes how we see ourselves and our world.

Design is not decoration.
It is strategy.
It is life.

Scientists just invented a completely new way to make videos with AI.

Itâ€™s called Interactive Motion Control.

Instead of prompting the motion with words, you can literally drag your cursor on the screen to precisely control how different things move.

But hereâ€™s the crazy partâ€¦

This tool lets you control that motion in real-time.

So as you draw it in, your new video is generating at the same time.

Itâ€™s like having a creative magic wand that actually works.

For example, letâ€™s say you have this photo of a wave coming out of a book.

And you want to turn that into a video where the wave crashes on the pages.

With this tool, you can literally draw in the exact motion path you want the wave to take.

And your new video will generate at 29 frames per second as you draw.

Youâ€™re not waiting for it to render.

That generation is happening instantly.

This is called real-time streaming and itâ€™s a massive breakthrough.

Not only can this method generate videos 900x faster than popular models, it can also make videos however long you want.

Thereâ€™s no maximum time limit.

And so the question isâ€¦how is that possible?

Cause these examples literally look like magic.

Well it turns out, the researchers who invented this, had a crazy ideaâ€¦

Intentional Memory Loss.

The reason AI video is so hard is because video models have to remember all the previous frames they generated before.

An 8 second video is 192 frames.

But here, theyâ€™re purposefully having the model forget all the frames in the middle.

All it remembers is the first frame and whatever happened in the last few seconds.

Now this model is the latest to come out of Adobe Research.

And so itâ€™s probably gonna launch in Adobe products at some point next year.

Imagine editing videos in Premiere Pro where you just draw camera movements and watch them generate instantly on your footage.

This whole model is called MotionStream.

And I think this is going to change the content creation game forever.

I made @yourstruly_khoifysh to post the random customs that probably wonâ€™t ever see the finish line, but I still adore them no less than my painted pieces. 
Now I want to show them off in a series of videos called Customizing Gunpla Is Fun (CGIF) to document the process, because the process is just as fun as the end goal.

STAGES OF A DOG'S LIFE

Dogs go through different stages of life, each with unique needs and behaviors. The puppy stage is a period of discovery and learning, where his energy and curiosity are at their maximum. As they grow and become young dogs, their body develops quickly and they begin to define their personality, habits and relationships with their environment.

Upon reaching adulthood, dogs usually stabilize their energy and behavior, showing greater maturity and more defined routines. Finally, in old age, they require special care and a more delicate approach to ensure their comfort and well-being. Understanding these stages allows us to offer a more complete and personalized care, especially in grooming services, where each phase requires attention and techniques adapted to the needs of the dog.

Two roads diverged in a yellow wood,

And sorry I could not travel both

And be one traveller, long I stood

And looked down one as far as I could

To where it bent in the undergrowth;

Then, I took the other, as just as fair,

And having perhaps the better claim,

Because it was grassy and wanted wear;

Though as for that the passing there

Had worn them really about the same,

And both that morning equally lay

In leaves, no step had trodden black.

Oh, I kept the first for another day!

Yet knowing how way leads on to way,

I doubted if I should ever come back.

I shall be telling this with a sigh

Somewhere ages and ages hence:

Two roads diverged in a wood, and Iâ€”

I took the one less travelled by,

And that has made all the difference.

The Road Not Takenâ€ by Robert Frost

Pan Am Smile vs. Duchenne Smile - 

A Pan Am smile is a polite, socially trained smile â€” it involves only the mouth, with no movement around the eyes. Itâ€™s often used in professional settings or customer service to appear friendly, even when the emotion isnâ€™t genuine.

A Duchenne smile, on the other hand, is a genuine expression of happiness. It engages both the mouth and the eyes â€” the corners of the eyes crinkle, and the face naturally brightens.

In short, the Pan Am smile is practiced, while the Duchenne smile is heartfelt â€” and people can easily tell the difference.

Shaq Spent $1 Million in a Day-and Learned a Big Lesson

After his basketball career took off, Shaquille O'Neal quickly realized just how much money he was making. One day, he received a $1 million paycheck-and decided it was time to enjoy the rewards.

First, he bought himself an AMG Mercedes. Then, he got the same exact car for his dad... and then one for his mom too. And he didn't stop there-he went on a luxury shopping spree that totaled the full million dollars.

But there was one thing he forgot to factor in: taxes. He had overestimated how much money he actually had to spend. Not long after, his accountant gave him a reality check-if he didn't learn how to manage his money properly, he could end up broke like many athletes after retirement.

When Michael Saylor says "your money in the bank isn't money," he means that what you think you own is just a promise, not actual value. When you deposit cash in a bank, it doesn't sit there-it's lent out, invested, or used by the bank. In return, you only get a digital number that represents what they owe you. Meanwhile, inflation keeps reducing its real purchasing power.

So, while it looks like you have money, it's actually losing value every day. Saylor believes true money should hold its value over time, like Bitcoin, which he calls "digital property." His point is that keeping savings in banks is like watching your wealth quietly erode while thinking it.

i really loved my time as a premed. 

whether that was doing public health research in the emergency medicine department or working with communities at risk for HIV as a tester & resource counselor.

but along the way, i started feeling called to something bigger. i realized there might be a way for me to scale my impact 100x, instead of only touching the lives of the people i could work with one-on-one.

i had so many hesitations. what would people think? how could i walk away from everything i worked so hard forâ€¦ all to not go to medical school?

but eventually, i realized: if not me, then who? who will help build the future of life sciences & healthcare? who will bring my lived experiences, my stories, and my voice into rooms that need it most?

if youâ€™ve felt the same or youâ€™re questioning premed, here are a few things that helped me decide to explore a path that blends science & innovation:

1) join fellowships or programs where you get more autonomy & hands-on design experience in science

2) reach out: cold email alumni & professors to ask for advice on navigating this field

3) take classes outside the traditional premed track (entrepreneurship, biotech innovation, modern tech in science)

4) get exposure in startups. it's the fastest way to learn how innovation actually happens

5) apply to internships that sit at the intersection of science, tech, and healthcare

Billionaires have found a legal way to avoid paying massive taxes, and itâ€™s all about being strategic with their wealth. 

Rather than taking a paycheck that gets taxed as income, theyâ€™re often compensated with stock options. 

This allows them to avoid the typical income tax rates. When they need to access cash, they donâ€™t sell their stockâ€”they simply take out loans using their shares as collateral. Since loans arenâ€™t counted as income, they donâ€™t owe taxes on that money.

On top of that, if they sell any stocks at a loss, they can use that loss to offset taxes on other profitable stock sales, further reducing their tax liability.

These are all legal tactics that help billionaires keep more of their wealth, and itâ€™s a game many play to minimize their tax bills.

Homeowners, be careful out there. A 79-year-old woman and her daughter just lost their family home in Queens through a title scam thatâ€™s becoming more and more common. When I look at Inuhomes today, itâ€™s hard to believe how far this quiet idea has come.
Behind every calm moment in this space, there were months of searching, uncertainty and small setbacks that tested me more than I expected.

Finding a unit felt impossible.
Spaces were too small, too dark, too expensive or simply not right for what I wanted to build.
And when I finally thought I found the one, URA rejected my first application.
It felt like the dream slipped through my fingers before it even began.

On top of that came the little mishaps.
Broken items arriving in the mail. Things I ordered coming damaged or not usable.
Small frustrations that built up on the days I was already tired.
A week before opening, my store flooded from a incorrectly installed faucet.

But through all of it, I kept reminding myself to stay patient.
To keep trying.
To believe that there were different paths I hadnâ€™t explored yet.
Because building something meaningful rarely follows a straight or perfect line.

Piece by piece, the setbacks shaped the vision.
The failed attempts pushed me toward better decisions.
And the challenges taught me that sometimes you grow the most when things donâ€™t go your way.

And now here we are.
A calm, warm, intentional space where dogs can feel safe and understood.
A place built from persistence, learning and a lot of heart.

If thereâ€™s one thing this journey taught me, itâ€™s this:
You donâ€™t need everything to go smoothly. You just need to keep believing in yourself and be willing to try again in a different way.

Thank you for being here as Inuhomes starts this new chapter.

SpaceXâ€™s Falcon 9 rocket went through an incredible journey of trial and error before achieving its first successful landing. The breakthrough came on December 21, 2015, when Falcon 9 touched down safely at Cape Canaveral after delivering satellites into orbit. This historic moment marked the first time an orbital-class rocket booster had ever been recovered for reuse â€” a major milestone in making spaceflight more cost-effective.

Before this achievement, SpaceX had faced several failed landing attempts on autonomous drone ships at sea. Some ended dramatically, with the booster tipping over, crashing, or exploding on impact. Yet each failure produced valuable data that helped SpaceX refine the engineering behind its landing system.

The eventual success proved that reusable rockets are not only possible but practical, reshaping the space industry by enabling more frequent and affordable missions.

Since then, Falcon 9 boosters have been landing consistently â€” on both land and drone ships â€” firmly establishing SpaceX as the leader in reusable rocket technology.

Petenis putri andalan Indonesia, Aldila Sutjiadi, menargetkan perolehan tiga medali emas pada SEA Games 2025 di Thailand. Target ini meliputi nomor beregu putri, ganda putri, dan ganda campuran, meningkat dari pencapaian dua emas yang ia raih pada edisi SEA Games sebelumnya.

Di nomor ganda putri, Aldila berpeluang dipasangkan dengan Janice Tjen, partnernya saat menjuarai WTA 250 Chennai Open 2025. Sementara itu, Christopher Rungkat juga menyatakan kesiapannya untuk kembali berkontribusi menyumbang emas, sejalan dengan target PP Pelti yang membidik total lima medali emas di ajang multievent Asia Tenggara tersebut.

Drawing atau pengundian grup Piala Dunia 2026 akan diselenggarakan di Kennedy Center, Washington DC, Amerika Serikat, pada Jumat (5/12) pukul 12.00 waktu setempat, atau Sabtu (6/12) pukul 00.00 WIB (tengah malam). Acara ini dapat disaksikan secara langsung melalui TVRI Sport, FIFA.com, dan kanal YouTube FIFA.

Pengundian ini akan membagi 48 negara peserta ke dalam 12 grup, di mana tuan rumah (AS, Kanada, Meksiko) bersama tim-tim kuat seperti Argentina, Spanyol, Prancis, dan Brasil menempati pot 1 sebagai unggulan. FIFA juga menerapkan format baru untuk mencegah tim-tim papan atas (peringkat tertinggi) bertemu sebelum babak semifinal dengan menempatkan mereka di jalur bagan (bracket) yang terpisah.

Timnas Putri Indonesia harus menelan kekalahan telak 0-8 dari tuan rumah Thailand pada laga perdana SEA Games 2025 di Stadion Chonburi, Kamis (4/12). Dominasi Thailand terlihat sejak awal, di mana gol pertama tercipta lewat bunuh diri Gea Yumanda pada menit ke-8, disusul serangkaian gol dari Pattaranan Aupachai, Silawan Intamee, Saowalak Pengngam, dan hattrick Jiraporn Mongkoldee di babak kedua.

Kekalahan ini menunjukkan perbedaan kelas yang mencolok antara kedua tim, terutama mengingat mayoritas pemain Indonesia minim jam terbang kompetisi dibandingkan Thailand yang sudah dua kali tampil di Piala Dunia Wanita. Meski sempat menciptakan beberapa peluang, skuad Garuda Pertiwi tak mampu membendung agresivitas Tim Gajah Putih yang terus menekan sepanjang laga.

Regardless of its destination, every overseas trip initiates on the same place: the airport. Following that thought, you could argue that Lightning's Ja-Car-Ta journey has a double start; his flight to Indoornesia required a transit in Towha, the capital of Qartar.
Now, is it possible to miss your start when you have two? You would deem it highly unlikely, but just like every other racing sport champion... So fast that they can reach the finish line, so slow they can make their way to the starting grid: due to circumstances, Lightning didn't have much time for the usual Instavroom shoots at the first airport, which means we pick up our documentation from here on out!

Throwback to October 9th, when Lightning landed at Towha International Airport around 23h local time. Too bad for him, his connecting flight to Ja-Car-Ta stranded him there for almost 10 HOURS! So, countering his boredom, he decided to go out and explore this self-proclaimed "Greatest Airport of the World"! When the quietest hours of the night approached and the endless corridors became emptier & emptier, the perfect opportunity arised to make these unique shots aswell as to try the famous treadmill railing trail [see video]. After some fooling around at the airport, it was time to fuel the tank and take a good nap, in await of the boarding time for the last flight on the schedule...

Meet the instrument that's accessible to everyone.

Nordoff and Robbins researcher, Jacob, developed this instrument that is designed to be easy for anyone to play. Originally designed for stroke rehabilitation, it can be used by anyone who has limited movement or dexterity, making it a great option in place of traditional instruments.

Named the ReHarp, it is programmed with sounds from a harp, that you can either play in chords or as individual notes. It was designed with funding from @cwpluscharity and is now used by Nordoff and Robbins music therapists around the country. 

Find out more about how it works via the link in bio.

Prompt for research âœ…
.
Literature Review Organization Prompt
â€œI want you to act as my research assistant and help me organize my literature review. I will provide you with a list of research papers, articles, and sources. For each source, extract and summarize the following details clearly: (1) complete citation, (2) research objective or question,
(3) theoretical framework, (4) methodology, (5) key variables, (6) major findings, (7) gaps identified, and (8) authorâ€™s conclusion. After extracting details from all sources, organize them in a comparative table and then synthesize them into themes (thematic clusters). Highlight how different studies support, contradict, or extend one another. Clearly identify the gaps that remain across the literature and propose possible directions for my research. Make sure the synthesis is structured under logical headings (such as theories used, methods, findings, gaps, and opportunities). Present both a structured table and a narrative summary that I can directly use in my literature review chapter.â€
.
Critical Analysis & Evaluation of Literature
â€œAct as my research assistant and help me critically analyze the literature on [insert topic/field].
For each paper, identify: (1) the research question and its significance, (2) the theoretical or conceptual framework, (3) methodology strengths and weaknesses, (4) contribution to the field,
(5) limitations noted by the authors, and (6) your critical evaluation of unspoken limitations or biases. After analyzing all papers, compare them side-by-side, showing how each paper contributes uniquely to the topic. Organize the evaluation into themes, highlighting strengths, contradictions, methodological gaps, and theoretical gaps. Provide me with both: (a) a structured critical evaluation table, and b) a written synthesis that demonstrates my ability to not just summarize but also critique the literature.â€
.

MODEL X â€” The Bridge That Redefined the Cello

Innovation in lutherie begins with asking the right questions.
For years, Luiz Amorim explored how to enhance sound transmission and responsiveness in the cello â€” and the answer became the Model X bridge.

Its distinctive, streamlined shape shortens the sound-transmission path, eliminating excess mass found in traditional bridges.
The result is a faster, more direct, and incredibly focused sound, with clarity that players immediately feel under the bow.

Today, the Model X is used on many Luiz Amorim cellos around the world, consistently offering more power, more definition, and a beautifully clean response.

A small componentâ€¦ with a big impact.

â€¢ Searching hundreds of peer-reviewed studies
â€¢ Understanding study design, methods, statistics
â€¢ Comparing results across multiple papers
â€¢ Identifying bias, funding sources, and limitations
â€¢ Weighing the totality of evidence â€” not one viral headline
â€”
Trusted sources scientists and doctors use:
â€¢ PubMed
â€¢ @cochranecollab Reviews
â€¢ NIH, FDA @nihgov @fda 
â€¢ WHO @who 
â€¢ Major peer-reviewed journals (NEJM, JAMA, Lancet, etc.)
@nejm @jamanetwork @thelancetgroup @sciencemagazine @nature_the_journal 
â€”
How do experts know which studies to trust:
â€¢ Design matters â€” randomized trials > observational studies > anecdotes
â€¢ Sample size â€” bigger, more diverse groups = more reliable
â€¢ Peer review â€” vetted by independent experts
â€¢ Reproducibility â€” can other teams find the same results?
â€¢ Conflicts of interest â€” who funded it?
â€¢ Consensus â€” one study rarely changes clinical practice
â€”
Real research is slow, rigorous, and collaborative.
Doing your own â€œsearchâ€ isnâ€™t the same as doing a scientific review.

Unlocking a number lock shouldnâ€™t be this easy. 

What looks like magic is actually pure mechanicsâ€”and a little bit of cleverness.
Hereâ€™s whatâ€™s really happening inside:
Every number lock has wheels, and each wheel has a tiny groove called a â€œgate.â€ When all the gates line up in the correct position, an internal locking bar drops into place and the lock pops open.
Normally, youâ€™d only reach those gates by dialing the right code.
But this technique? It bypasses all of that.
By sliding a thin piece of paper between the wheels and feeling for the subtle moment when it falls into the gate, you can identify the exact digit for that wheel.
That tiny drop is your signal. Repeat the process on each section, and youâ€™ve decoded the entire lockâ€”without ever knowing the original combination. 
Itâ€™s a brilliant demonstration of how analog mechanisms can be cracked using nothing but touch, precision, and patience.
And honestly? It shows just how much engineering goes into even the simplest everyday toolsâ€”and how understanding those mechanics can unlock them (literally).
Security isnâ€™t just about complexity. Itâ€™s about understanding vulnerability.

Ukrainian actress Tania Galakhova powerfully portrayed what it's like to live with depression through her raw and emotionally grounded performance. She captured the silent heaviness, numbness, and isolation that come with the condition - not through exaggerated emotion, but through quiet expressions and subtle gestures that reveal the inner struggle. Fever isnâ€™t just a symptom - itâ€™s a finely tuned biological mechanism that helps your immune system respond faster and more efficiently. Watch this reel to see immune cells moving faster when the temperature rises.

Small increases in body temperature (just 1â€“2Â°C) have profound effects on immune cells, including dendritic cells, T cells, macrophages, and neutrophils, by directly influencing their motility, polarization, chemotaxis, and target-search behavior - all independently of the surrounding tissue environment.
â€¨Live imaging in zebrafish embryos, mouse tissue explants, and 3D cultures shows that these temperature shifts accelerate cell migration, tissue exploration, and arrival at wounds or lymphatic vessels, while cooler conditions can delay immune responses by 10â€“20 hours. Experiments using lymphatic vessel geometries confirmed that even subtle thermokinetic changes significantly impact encounter rates between immune cells and their targets.â€¨
Whatâ€™s driving this temperature effect?â€¨A slight rise in temperature makes Myosin II work harder, tightening the actomyosin network and allowing immune cells to move faster and more efficiently. This is a rapid and reversible â€œthermo-boostâ€ that enhances immune surveillance.
â€¨Thatâ€™s why fever is most beneficial during infections or tissue injury, where a slightly higher temperature can give your immune system the edge it needs to respond quickly and effectively - essentially turning up the speed of your bodyâ€™s natural defense network.â€¨
Credits: Company-Garrido I. et al. Developmental Cell 2025

Most people will never witness a moment like this because almost no ships on Earth can survive the journey to the true North Pole. ğŸŒğŸ§Š

Reaching the geographic North Pole is one of the hardest feats in modern navigation. The Arctic Ocean is not open water. It is a shifting desert of multi-year sea ice, with slabs thicker than houses that are constantly moving, cracking, and refreezing.
This environment destroys ordinary vessels in minutes.

Only two ships on the planet are engineered to break through terrain like this:

Nuclear icebreakers are built like floating battering rams. With hulls over two inches thick and reactors providing continuous power, they can ride up onto solid ice and crush it under their own weight. Charcot uses a next-generation PC2 ice-class design, one of the strongest classifications on Earth, which allows it to navigate pressure ridges, frozen waves, and moving ice fields that would destroy almost any other ship.

Even with all of this engineering power, these vessels can only reach the Pole during certain months when the ice is at its weakest. That is how extreme this region truly is.

So when these two ships meet at the top of the world, you are seeing something that can only occur under the rarest conditions. It is human engineering pushing into one of the most hostile environments on the planet.

NASA Rover Detects Electric Sparks in Mars Dust Devils, Storms ğŸŒªï¸

NASAâ€™s Perseverance Mars rover has recorded the sounds of electrical discharges â€”sparks â€” and mini-sonic booms in dust devils on Mars. Long theorized, the phenomenon has now been confirmed through audio and electromagnetic recordings captured by the roverâ€™s SuperCam microphone. The discovery, published Nov. 26 in the journal Nature, has implications for Martian atmospheric chemistry, climate, and habitability, and could help inform the design of future robotic and human missions to Mars.

SuperCam has recorded 55 distinct electrical events over the course of the mission, beginning on the missionâ€™s 215thMartian day, or sol, in 2021. Sixteen have been recorded when dust devils passed directly over the rover.

Decades before Perseverance landed, scientists theorized that the friction generated by tiny dust grains swirling and rubbing against each other in Martian dust devils could generate enough of an electrical charge to eventually produce electrical arcs. Called the triboelectric effect, itâ€™s the phenomenon at play when someone walks over a carpet in socks and then touches a metal doorknob, generating a spark. In fact, that is about the same level of discharge as what a Martian dust devil might produce.

Deep in your brainstem sits a region called the trigeminocervical nucleus the convergence point where sensory information from your jaw and face (trigeminal nerve) meets sensory information from your upper neck (cervical nerves C1-C3).
 
Hereâ€™s where it gets interesting.
 
A 2025 scoping review analyzing 83 studies confirmed that this neurological junction creates bidirectional pain referral patterns. 
 
Pain signals from your jaw can register as neck pain. Dysfunction in your upper cervical spine can manifest as jaw pain, facial pain, or even headaches. 

When the jaw muscles tighten or the joint becomes irritated, pain signals travel through the trigeminal nerve into the trigeminocervical nucleus.

Because this area shares pathways with the upper neck nerves, the brain canâ€™t clearly separate where the pain comes from. 

The result is that jaw tension can be felt as neck pain, headaches, or facial pressure even though the source is in the jaw.

Which means that your brain processes jaw position and neck position as interconnected data streams.

Roasted Cabbage (method)

poached chicken congee ğŸ²

Ingredients: 
+ 1 cup jasmine rice, toasted
+ 8 cups chicken broth (from poaching the chicken)
+ 1 whole chicken
+ 7â€“8 slices fresh ginger
+ Â½ onion
+ 3-4 green onions
+ 1 tbsp chicken bouillon 
+ 2 teaspoons salt (adjust to taste)
+ Dash of fish sauce
+ Dash of sugar

Toppings (Highly recommended ):
+ Chopped scallions and cilantro
+ Fried shallots or garlic
+ Chopped chilies

Instructions:
	1. In a large pot, add the whole chicken, water, salt, ginger, green onion, and onion. Bring to a boil, then lower to a gentle simmer.
	2.	Simmer until the chicken is cooked through (about 45â€“60 minutes). Remove the chicken, shred the meat, and set aside. Strain and reserve the broth.
	3.	Toast the jasmine rice in a dry pan until fragrant. Add it to the reserved broth. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until the rice breaks down into a thick porridge (about 60â€“90 minutes). Add the chicken bouillon, fish sauce, and a dash of sugar. Adjust add salt and adjust as needed.
	4.	Ladle the congee into bowls, top with shredded chicken and your favorite toppings. (I did chillies, green onions, and fried shallots)

Vegan Fluffy Carrot Cake with One Bowl and a Whisk
Ingredients
500 g self raising flour
370 g orange juice
280 g sugar
100 g sunflower oil
100 g raisins
140 g walnuts
150 g grated carrot
100 g chocolate sprinkles
1 tsp cinnamon
â€”
powdered sugar
Instructions
In a bowl add orange juice sugar oil raisins cinnamon and mix well
Add the flour and stir just until combined
Add the walnuts carrot and chocolate sprinkles and mix
Transfer to a greased and floured 25x30 cm baking tray and bake at 170 degrees Celsius bottom and top heat for 1 hour
Let it cool cut into pieces and sprinkle with powdered sugar

â€¢ my MIL told me the best flour to use is the Golden Temple brand (yellow or purple bag) Iâ€™m not using it in this video but I usually do and totally feel the difference. 

â€¢ temperature is also an imp factor. Gas stove, keep on simmer high - low. Induction stove: I usually keep it between 2-3. If youâ€™re seeing dark brown spots on your roti, take your pan off for a bit because itâ€™s probably too hot. You want it to fully cook on the inside

ğŸ¤POV: This is what happens when simple ingredients get 50 minutes of love.A silky nest of linguine, coated in slow-cooked tomato sauce, crowned with the sweetest little seafood bite that melts the moment it hits your tongue.Fresh basil. Olive oil. Sunshine. Thatâ€™s it. Save this.
Ingredients (2â€“3 servings)
	â€¢	200 g linguine
	â€¢	8â€“10 shrimp, cleaned and shell removed
	â€¢	1 medium onion, finely chopped
	â€¢	2 garlic cloves, minced
	â€¢	Â½ tsp garlic powder
	â€¢	Salt (to taste)
	â€¢	1 tbsp tomato paste
	â€¢	4-5 fresh tomatoes, grated or finely chopped
	â€¢	2â€“3 tbsp olive oil
	â€¢	Fresh basil leaves
	â€¢	black pepper
Optional: chili flakes, a splash of white wine
Method
1. Build the base of the sauce
Heat the olive oil in a pan over medium heat.
Add the chopped onion and sautÃ© until soft and fragrant.
Stir in the minced garlic, then add the garlic powder and a little salt so it blooms in the oil.
2. Add tomato paste and fresh tomatoes
Mix in the tomato paste and let it cook for 1â€“2 minutes to deepen the flavour.
Add the fresh tomatoes and stir well.
Lower the heat and let the sauce simmer slowly for about 50 minutes, until thick, sweet, and reduced.
3. Cook the shrimp
Add the shrimp directly into the sauce and cook for about 6 minutes, until just tender.
Remove the shrimp from the pan and set them aside so they donâ€™t overcook.
4. Add the pasta
Boil the linguine in salted water until al dente.Transfer the linguine into the tomato sauce and toss well until itâ€™s fully coated.
5. Finish the dish Place the shrimp back on top of the pasta.Add fresh basil leaves just before serving for fragrance and brightness.#pasta#pastalove #pastarecipe#seafood#seafoodpasta#shrimp#shrimprecipes#foodreel#foodreels#easyrecipes#dinnerideasğŸ´ #italiancooking#italianfood#comfortfood#freshingrediants#reelitfeel#yum#pastarecipe#basil#recipes#recipe#linguine#linguinepasta#homecooking #pastalovers

Aggiungete riso a chicco lungo, passata di pomodoro, due foglie di alloro, coprite con brodo di pollo e portate a cottura, pochi minuti prima che sia pronto unite i gamberoni puliti, il pollo e la salsiccia ed eliminate l'alloro, aggiustare di sale e mescolate, il mio tocco?

Ã¨ nato come una prova per utilizzare i mandarini in frigo e si Ã¨ trasformato nel mio piatto invernale preferito âœ¨ğŸŠ

100 ml vino bianco secco
4 cucchiai olio extravergine dâ€™oliva
3 cucchiai succo dâ€™arancia
3 cucchiai succo di limone
2 cucchiai senape in grani
3 cucchiai zucchero di canna
2 finocchi 500 g circa
1,3 kg cosce di pollo con la pelle
400 g clementine bio
foglie di timo
2,5 cucchiaini semi di finocchio
2,5 cucchiaini sale
1,5 cucchiaini pepe nero macinato
prezzemolo fresco

Mettete i primi 6 ingredienti in una grossa ciotola insieme a 2 cucchiaini e mezzo di sale e 1 e mezzo di pepe nero. Sbattete bene il tutto e mettete da parte.
Spuntate i finocchi e tagliateli a metÃ  nel senso della lunghezza. Ogni metÃ  tagliatela in 4 spicchi. Mettete i finocchi nel liquido insieme alle cosce di pollo, alla clementine affettate, il timo, i semi di finocchio e di anice.
Rimestate bene usando le mani; lasciate marinare in frigo tutta la notte.
Il giorno dopo preriscaldate il forno ventilato a 200-220Â°C. Trasferite il pollo e la marinata in una teglia da forno circa 30x37cm (gli ingredienti devono formare un solo strato). Controllate che la pelle ricopra per bene le cosce di pollo.
Mettete in forno. Cuocete per 30 minuti, rigirate le cosce e fate cuocere per altri 15 minuti.
Trasferite in un piatto da portata cosce, finocchi e clementine, mentre versate in una salsiera il sughetto. Nel caso in cui non si fosse ben addensato, restringete la salsa qualche minuto sul fuoco, mentre tenete in caldo il pollo. â™¥ï¸

An unforgettable evening at @ishqnyc Ishq Indian Restaurant in NYC! From the first sip of their incredible cocktails to the last bite of the decadent Kala Jamun Tart, every moment was pure bliss.

We started with unique appetizers like the Gupchup (gulgappas with ragada peas), Soya Malai Chop, Nizami Lamb Chops, and the flavorful Sharabi Chicken Tikkaâ€”each dish bursting with flavor. For the mains, we savored the rich and creamy Butter Chicken, the aromatic Dum Ka Gosht, perfectly paired with Romali Roti, Naan, and Saffron Rice.

Every bite was divine, and the stunning presentation elevated the entire experience. If youâ€™re in NYC and craving exceptional Indian cuisine, Ishq is a must-visit! âœ¨

Kaizen Omakase is such a beautiful spot!
The ambience was stunningâ€”intimate, elegant, and perfect for a special night out. The whole experience was truly memorable from the moment we walked in.

We started with a few appetizers that were absolutely delicious. The rock shrimp tempura had the perfect balance of sweetness and spice, the tuna tartare was fresh and flavorful, and the Japanese honey-glazed ribs were melt-in-your-mouth goodâ€”sweet, sticky, and so satisfying.

Then came the highlight: their 15-course omakase. Every piece was crafted to perfectionâ€”so fresh, thoughtful, and full of flavor. We also tried a few hand rolls, and each one was just as impressiveâ€”clean, balanced, and incredibly tasty.

The drinks were just as memorableâ€”the spicy matcha margarita had a bold kick, and the mango cocktail was tropical and refreshing. We even tried a couple of fun shots: the ginger vodka shot and the wasabi shotâ€”both unique and flavorful.

Sunny was so hospitableâ€”he welcomed us warmly and explained each course with such passion and detail.
Canâ€™t wait to go back again and experience it all over again!

Located inside the Surfriders Resort, Sirens is a great little spot to grab a bite and enjoy the views of Fogarty Beach. We went for breakfast and enjoyed a well made Eggs Benedict with hot coffee and a lovely place to watch the snow fall. The hashbrowns were nice and crispy, and they eggs were poached perfectly. If you want a classic breakfast, you won't be disappointed. 

The wait staff is very friendly and efficient. The dining area has large windows over most of the space, so you get a great view no matter where you sit. Our food came out quickly. The parking lot is shared with the resort, so it might be busier sometimes over others.

There is nothing better than the only place to stop for lunch being freaking FANTASTIC! We stopped in at Frostop Drive-in in Idaho on our way back from Montana, and it was such a good idea. Had the chance to check out the recently revamped A Street Pub for my weekly lunch out with my love. We each ordered a sandwich. I had the Drunk-n-Dunk with onion rings. It was fantastic. The beer cheese sauce is so good, and the onion rings have the perfect amount of batter to be crispy without falling apart. He got the broken window chicken sandwich with Cajun fries. He loved the big chunks of avocado. We both enjoyed the way they toasted the whole sandwich.
The service was great. We ate outside and didn't get forgotten at all. The outdoor dining area is perfect for summer eating. The food came out quickly and hot. We got everything we requested, and all with a smile and kind word. We will definitely be back for more meals.

Atomic Runner is an arcade side-scrolling shooter platform video game developed and published by Data East in 1988. 

It was ported to the Sega Genesis in 1992 and the Sharp X68000 in 1993. 

In the game, the player takes the role of Chelnov, a coal miner who miraculously survives the malfunction and explosion of a nuclear power plant. 

Chelnov's body gains superhuman abilities due to the massive amount of radiation given off by the explosion, and a secret organization seeks to harness those abilities for its own evil purposes. 

Chelnov must battle and defeat the secret organization using his newfound abilities.

Apricot bulida fruit tree - R195 per 5L bag

AKey Characteristics:
- *Growth Habit*: Semi-upright with a medium tree size, growing up to 4m high and 4m wide.
- *Fruit*: Firm, sweet, and juicy with a smooth, velvety skin and bright orange color. The flesh is light yellow, and the fruit is suitable for canning.
- *Pollination*: Self-pollinating, but it's always beneficial to have multiple trees for better fruit set.
- *Disease Susceptibility*: No specific information available, but regular spraying can help prevent common stone fruit diseases.

*Growing Conditions:*

- *Sunlight*: Full sun is essential for optimal fruit production.
- *Soil*: Well-draining soil with a slightly acidic pH is preferred.
- *Watering*: Regular watering, especially during flowering and fruiting stages, is crucial.
- *Fertilization*: Balanced fertilizer application promotes healthy growth and fruit production.

Bloody Mary Refrigerator Pickles 

Listen. These are refrigerator pickles. Not pioneer-woman, boiling-jars, sealing-lids, summon-the-ghost-of-your-grandma canning pickles. These live in the fridge. They thrive in the fridge. They belong in the fridge.

Ingredients:
	â€¢	1 small bag mini cucumbers, quartered
	â€¢	A few jalapeÃ±o slices (because you like a little chaos)
	â€¢	4 garlic cloves, smashed like your last nerve
	â€¢	Splash of lime (donâ€™t be like me â€” actually add it)
	â€¢	1 tsp horseradish
	â€¢	A few shakes Worcestershire
	â€¢	A few shakes Cholula Chipotle
	â€¢	Celery salt, pepper

Brine:
	â€¢	Â½ cup white vinegar
	â€¢	1 Â½ cups Clamato
	â€¢	A little over 2 tbsp pickling salt

Method:
	1.	Warm the vinegar, Clamato, and pickling salt in a pot just until the salt dissolves. If it boils, start over and donâ€™t look at me.
	2.	Let that cool down to room temp â€” the cucumbers did not ask to be scalded.
	3.	Pack your jar with the cucumbers, jalapeÃ±o, garlic, and all your seasonings.
	4.	Pour the cooled brine over everything, seal it, and put it straight into the fridge.
	5.	Leave it alone for three whole days.
	â€¢	Shake the jar like a maraca if you must, but do not open it.
	â€¢	Donâ€™t taste it, donâ€™t poke it, donâ€™t â€œjust checkâ€ â€” hands off.

When the three days are up?
Youâ€™re a pickle-making menace, and the world is better for it. #pickles #diy #recipe #bloodymarypickles #bloodymary

Berlinâ€™s Red Square 
A 20-second tour of socialist modernism!

Swipe through the iconic architecture of Alexanderplatz & Berlin-Mitte. This is the heart of GDR urban planning!

Berlin TV Tower (Berliner Fernsehturm) - The iconic 368m needle of Berlin, built between 1965-1969. Architects: Hermann Henselmann, JÃ¶rg Streitparth, et al.

Haus des Lehrers & Mosaic Frieze - The â€œHouse of the Teachersâ€ (1962-64) by Hermann Henselmann, famous for its stunning 125m long mosaic.

Press Cafe / Haus des Berliner Verlags - This 1970s building features the monumental mural â€œThe Press as an Organiserâ€ by Willi Neubert, depicting a Marxist view of the press. Architects: Swora, Hanslik, Derdau, et al.

Weltzeituhr (World Time Clock) - The legendary meeting point at Alex, designed by Erich John and opened in 1969.

All footage courtesy of BACU.

caption:
Environmental Rhythms v.3

For this exploration I recorded the view from a moving train where passing trains, poles and station lights create a constant flow of repeating shapes.
Each object that cuts across the frame becomes a rhythmic event inside the modular system triggering different fragments of audio and shifting parameters at every step.
This technique keeps revealing fresh patterns beyond the grid and continues to open new directions for creative sound design.

For the next 5 weeks, do these 6 things if youâ€™re feeling overwhelmed at home, and I promise youâ€™ll feel better before 2026.

1. For a week, every time you feel the urge to shop, try setting a timer for 5-10 minutes and decluttering something instead. Your car, your desk, a kitchen drawer, the reusable grocery bagsâ€¦ anything. It will give your brain a dopamine hit (just like shopping does!) AND it will help you feel better at home. 

2. Adopt the mindset that more is not always better. When you have a good thing, appreciate that thing, take care of it, use it, and enjoy it. You donâ€™t need to seek out another, or more. (Maybe donâ€™t buy the same sweater in 4 colors?)

3. Unfollow influencers on all social media platforms. If theyâ€™re constantly linking products, I can almost guarantee you that theyâ€™re doing you more harm than good.

4. Write a gratitude list, every day. Taking just 3 minutes to write down things that youâ€™re grateful for will train your brain to have an abundance mindset and youâ€™ll notice the good in your life even more. 

5. Embrace the â€œrule of oneâ€ in just one area. Try it out. One good winter coat. Or one good water bottle. Or one good pair of sunglasses. Or one good bag. 

6. Follow the one in, two out rule. (One new item comes in, two other items need to be donated). â€¨â€¨And remember, we were never meant to manage this much stuff â¤ï¸

which of these will you try?

caption:
Babel

In a world built from binary-black and white, truth and illusion-we march forward without knowing where we are going. This is not just religion, nor just ritual. It is the performance of authority in a society that no longer believes in singular truths. The bishopâ€™s silence is louder than prophecy, his shadow stitched into the chaos beneath his feet.
Each square beneath him is a decision, a doctrine, a decree-but none leads to resolution.
Politics and religion blend here, not to offer clarity, but to confuse. We build, like Babelâ€™s architects, higher and higher, driven not by vision but inertia. We do.
We act. We legislate. We proclaim. And yet we ask: where does this all lead?
The video doesnâ€™t answer. It mirrors. It resists narrative. A frozen frame in a story too complex to tell-an opera without libretto, a ritual stripped of salvation.

Growing mistletoe is one of my favourite winter gardening projects. If you have ever wondered how to grow mistletoe from fresh berries this is the simplest propagation method. The viscin inside the berry is naturally sticky which helps the seed attach to the host branch. I am working with hazel although mistletoe grows very well on apple, hawthorn and lime which are classic mistletoe host trees in the UK.

February is the best time for mistletoe propagation because the berries are fully ripe and germinate more reliably. Mistletoe is a hemiparasite so it relies on the host tree for water and nutrients which makes it a fascinating plant to grow in a home garden or orchard. Germination takes time and a fruiting mistletoe plant usually develops within three to five years.

Growing your own mistletoe for Christmas feels incredibly rewarding. This ancient evergreen has long been linked with renewal, protection and the tradition of sharing a Christmas kiss so nurturing your own sprig brings a little extra meaning to the festive season. âœ¨ğŸ„

Cucumber Kimchi ğŸ¥’ğŸŒ¶ï¸ Made using homegrown cucumbers for a little #gardentotable moment ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€ğŸŒ¾ğŸƒ I've been enjoying it with most of my dinners as the perfect little side dish - it's refreshing, crunchy and so flavourful! 

ğŸ‘‡ SAVE THIS RECIPEğŸ‘‡

Base:
3 medium cucumbers
1/2 - 1 tbsp coarse sea salt
2 stalks green onions, thinly sliced (or garlic chives if you have them!)
1 small carrot, thinly sliced or shredded

Paste:
2 tbsp gochugaru 
1/2 apple, grated (I like to use this instead of sugar, but you can sub with a few tsp sweetener)
1/4 brown onion, finely grated
1 tbsp vegan fish sauce
1 clove garlic, finely grated
1 tsp grated ginger

Method: 
1. Wash your cucumbers well, halve lengthways then thinly slice them on a slight angle. 
2. Transfer to a large bowl and sprinkle enough sea salt to coat all of the cucumber slices (I used just under 1 tbsp). Toss well and set aside for at least 15-20 minutes or until liquid has pooled to the bottom of the bowl. 
3. Discard the liquid, then rinse the cucumber a few times to get rid of any excess salt. I like to taste it just to be sure. Drain/dry well. 
4. In the meantime, add all of the paste ingredients into a bowl and mix well to combine. 
5. Add the cucumber, carrots and green onions to the paste and mix well until everything is evenly coated. 
6. Serve immediately or transfer into a container and store it in the fridge (I do this since I personally prefer fresh kimchi). If you want it to be more fermented and sour, leave at room temperature overnight or for 24 hours before storing in the fridge. Enjoy ğŸ’š

The Samsung Galaxy Z Trifold is so exclusive in Singapore that you need a special invitation before you can even think about owning it. Money alone cannot save you here.

Super thin at 3.9 millimetres, basically the width of a USB C port, and the U shaped fold feels easy to handle. Try to close it the wrong way and it gives you a haptic warning, like a mini safety officer.

Folded, it is chunky at 309 grams, but still manageable. Open it up and that massive display is perfect for dramas, browsing and flipping orientation to read long documents comfortably.

There is one disappointment, no screen continuity. Apps must reload when you unfold, which really breaks the flow.

But for multitasking, the screen size is a dream. Split screen is fluid, DeX is built in, and wireless projection gives you another display if you want to go full mobile-workflow mode.

It is futuristic, niche and definitely a flex.
Would you buy it if Samsung invited you?

We need to make movies corny again.

I recently rewatched The Holiday (directed by Nancy Meyers, production design by Jon Hutman) on the big screen, and not only is this just one of my favorite Christmas movies of all time, itâ€™s also just a gorgeously photographed film.

I mean, this movie was shot by Dean Cundey, who you guys know from my video about The Parent Trap and why movies donâ€™t look like movies anymore. And The Holiday is another fantastic example of this.

The way that Dean lit faces in this movie is unbelievable.
Thereâ€™s an earnestness and this magical, romantic fairy-tale feel to it that we just donâ€™t see often these days.

Thereâ€™s a common consensus that people should be lighting spaces instead of faces. And I think that is contributing to why things look very bland and boring these days.

I want people to light faces.

Watch this scene where Jude Law walks towards the camera.
He has a key light on him.
Then he goes into a little bit of darkness, and then he has another key light on him.

That means he had to hit his marks for focus, but also had to hit the marks for the light to hit his face properly.

This is artistry.
This is painting with light.
And this is something that Dean Cundey has always been a master at.

Itâ€™s not just the lighting.
Itâ€™s everything from the meticulously crafted production design and wardrobe. This whole movie just feels cozy at all times.

I think what bothers me the most is that thereâ€™s nothing in this movie that couldnâ€™t be replicated today. And weâ€™re making romantic comedies and Christmas movies left, right, and center, but none of them really have the magic of THE HOLIDAY.

So this is my petitionâ€¦ Bring back corny lighting.

Because the holidays are a whimsical, weird, cozy, romantic, corny time. And the movies should feel that way too.

We need to make movies corny again.

I recently rewatched The Holiday (directed by Nancy Meyers, production design by Jon Hutman) on the big screen, and not only is this just one of my favorite Christmas movies of all time, itâ€™s also just a gorgeously photographed film.

I mean, this movie was shot by Dean Cundey, who you guys know from my video about The Parent Trap and why movies donâ€™t look like movies anymore. And The Holiday is another fantastic example of this.

The way that Dean lit faces in this movie is unbelievable.
Thereâ€™s an earnestness and this magical, romantic fairy-tale feel to it that we just donâ€™t see often these days.

Thereâ€™s a common consensus that people should be lighting spaces instead of faces. And I think that is contributing to why things look very bland and boring these days.

I want people to light faces.

Watch this scene where Jude Law walks towards the camera.
He has a key light on him.
Then he goes into a little bit of darkness, and then he has another key light on him.

That means he had to hit his marks for focus, but also had to hit the marks for the light to hit his face properly.

This is artistry.
This is painting with light.
And this is something that Dean Cundey has always been a master at.

Itâ€™s not just the lighting.

The need for unions is more obvious now than ever.

Starbucks currently has one of the largest CEO-to-base-worker pay gaps in America. In 2024, CEO Brian Niccol made $95.8 million, while the median barista made $14,674. 

As the company's sales decline, Niccol has prioritized higher-ups' wages over those of base workers, laying off over 900 non-retail employees and closing multiple US and Canadian stores. 

As Starbucks directs its priorities to satisfying its managers, the hardworking employees of this company are consistently neglected. 

The Republican Party has consistently downplayed the attitude toward unions, or as I like to think of it, the party that consistently prioritizes the needs of the rich over everyday Americans like you and I.
 
If the Republican Party is not going to fight for the needs and benefits of hard-working Americans, we need unions to ensure fair working conditions and wages.

The third episode of the Swimbo Podcast features a conversation between the host and his friend Andrey, whom he met in college. Andrey discusses his significant life transition, moving from being homeschooled and attending a Mennonite school to the college environment. He recounts his most memorable college moment: the start of their friendship, which began with a discussion about vapes and him revealing his large collection stored in his locker. While he misses the friends he made, he is glad to be finished with homework and assignments. The conversation shifts to Andreyâ€™s spiritual journey. Raised in a Christian household, he always believed in God, but admits he held a grudge against Him for perceived difficult life circumstances. Andrey ultimately shares that he accepted Jesus Christ as his Lord and Savior at a youth conference after a period of internal struggle and reflection.

USCIS announced today that the maximum validity period for certain Employment Authorization Documents (EADs) has been shortened from 5 years to 18 months.

USCIS says this change allows for more frequent vetting to detect fraud and ensure that individuals seeking work do not pose a threat to public safety or promote harmful ideologies.

Har mulk ka apna ek unique culture hota hai, aur festivals us culture ki sabse zyada bright aur lively expression hote hain. Agar aap travel ko sirf sightseeing nahi, balkay real experiences ke liye karte ho, toh cultural festivals aapko woh energy dete hain jo kisi aur cheez mein nahi milti. Yeh events ek mulk ki rooh, riwayat aur logon ki kahaniyan zinda kar dete hain.

Agar aap colors aur creativity pasand karte hain, Spain ka La Tomatina aur India ka Holi do bilkul alag lekin equally vibrant celebrations hain. Dono festivals aapko crowds, colors aur pure joy ka mix feel karwate hain. Yeh woh moments hain jahan log boundaries, backgrounds, aur barriers bhool kar ek saath celebrate karte hain, aur yehi travel ko meaningful banata hai.
Japan ka Gion Matsuri, Venice ka Carnival, ya Mexico ka DÃ­a de los Muertos, in sab festivals ki apni depth aur history hoti hai. Yeh sirf events nahi, balke centuries purani traditions ka continuation hote hain. Yahan jaakar aap ko pata chalta hai ke ek society apni roots ko kis tarah celebrate karti hai. Har event aapko ek story sunata hai, bas farq sirf itna hota hai ke yeh stories dance, masks, rituals ya parades ke zariye share hoti hain.

Cultural festivals ka sabse khubsurat element yeh hota hai ke yeh aapko local communities ke beech le jaate hain. Aap unke saath khaate hain, unki rituals dekhte hain, aur unke saath moments share karte hain jo aap kisi guidebook mein nahi dekh sakte. Yeh interactions aapko travel ko ek deeper level par samajhne ka mauqa dete hain.

In the early years of the Cold War, the United States was racing to understand nuclear weapons on a deeper level. Most tests up to that point were atmospheric, producing massive mushroom clouds that spread radioactive fallout across wide areas. But in 1957, everything changed.
That year, the U.S. carried out Operation Rainier, the first fully contained underground nuclear test in history. It took place at the Nevada Test Site, roughly 65 miles from Las Vegas. The device was buried inside a sealed horizontal tunnel carved into solid rock, designed to trap the explosion beneath the surface.

When the bomb detonated, its energy was released in microseconds.
â€¨No blinding flash.â€¨No rising cloud.â€¨No surface shockwave.

Instead, the blast created a massive underground cavity, vaporizing rock instantly and fusing layers of earth into glass. Seismographs around the world recorded the tremor, proving that underground testing could be powerful yet far more controlled.

This single experiment reshaped nuclear research.â€¨It allowed scientists to study shockwaves, containment, and structural effects while drastically reducing radioactive fallout. And it paved the way for hundreds of underground tests that followed during the arms race.
What looks like barren desert in the footage is actually one of the most technologically significant landscapes in American history, a place where science, strategy, and risk collided beneath the surface.

If this is the future of *educated* Canada, God help us.

As children grow into teens, you may notice some changes in their behaviour and emotions. These shifts are a normal part of development and growing independence 

Some common signs include:

* Wanting more privacy (closing doors, time alone)
* Mood shifts â€“ irritability, tearfulness, or frustration
* Spending more time with friends, less with family
* Changes in sleep patterns â€“ staying up late, sleeping in
* Becoming more self-conscious about appearance
* Increased sensitivity to criticism or embarrassment
* Testing limits and questioning family rules
* Fluctuating energy and motivation levels

Remember: these changes are part of your teen learning who they are and how they fit into the world

Intimacy gets talked about like itâ€™s one thing, lovely, rose-tinted and romantic. But intimacy is far bigger, stranger, and more personal than that.

Often, Intimacy is the feeling of being known. Seen. Safe. Connected.

Sometimes in emotional ways. 
Sometimes physical. 
Sometimes intellectual, spiritual, playful, or in another deeply private way.

And what counts as intimacy depends entirely on who you are, how you love, how you communicate, and what your nervous system has learned about closeness. (Not helpful for definitions, but helpful for personal understanding).

Some people feel intimacy through deep conversation. Others through shared laughter. Others through s_x. Others through stillness. Others through routine. None of this is right or wrong - itâ€™s just deeply human variation.

Intimacy grows from context: your attachment style, your upbringing, your mental health, your stress levels, your s_xual scripts, your cultural background, your history, your relationship dynamics, your hormones, and the environment youâ€™re in.
Itâ€™s teachable. 
Itâ€™s flexible. 
It can change across life stages, partners, experiences & healing. 

And the more you understand your own intimacy language, the easier it becomes to build relationships that feel grounded, consensual, nourishing, and honest.
Intimacy isnâ€™t a skill you â€˜haveâ€™ or â€˜dont haveâ€™.
Itâ€™s a process - one your body and mind are always shaping, reshaping, and responding to.

Top three myths about couples therapy â€” debunked with warmth and insight

Myth 1: Couples therapy is only for relationships on the brink of breaking.
Truth: Therapy is about growth and connection, not just crisis. It helps couples build stronger bonds before problems get too big.

Myth 2: Therapy will blame one partner or dig up past mistakes.
Truth: It's a judgment-free space focused on understanding and healing together, not assigning blame.

Myth 3: Couples therapy is just talking â€” it won't change anything.
Truth: With proven methods like the Gottman Method, therapy teaches practical communication skills that change how you relate.

If you and your partner want to deepen understanding and renew connection, therapy might be the warm, supportive space you need.

Have questions or want to learn more? Let's start a conversation about how to grow together.

Bratislava in winter feels like stepping into a vintage film reel - cold air, soft fog rolling through the streets, and that quiet, cozy vibe that makes the city feel extra magical.

From warming up with traditional Slovak food and sweets, to wandering the Christmas markets with mulled wine in hand, every corner has a particular charm. âœ¨

I loved the mix of Brutalist architecture and the artsy/retro scene - raw, bold, and beautifully nostalgic. Even the visit to the Slovan Bratislava (@skslovanbratislava) stadium (closed - meh) and the fanshop had their own kind of character.

A humble city with a big soul.
Definitely worth a visit!

Staying hydrated is one of the most important things you can do to maintain health and performance!

âœ… Most athletes need 90â€“120 oz. of fluid per day + minerals lost through sweat.

Simple tips to stay on track:
âœ” Weigh in before and after training.
âœ” Rehydrate with 16â€“24 oz. per pound lost.
âœ” Include minerals during workouts >60 min.

Why it matters: Even a 2% loss in body weight from dehydration can:
âš  Cause headaches
âš  Drop speed, power & strength
âš  Increase risk of cramping & injury
âš  Reduce circulation & cooling ability

Pro tips for optimal performance:
- Drink water consistently (set alarms if needed!)
- Pack minerals/electrolytes for long sessions
-Add 30â€“60g of carbs per hour of intense activity

Some six years ago, I photographed a campaign for the Commission for the Rights of Persons with Disability (CRPD), celebrating the normality, strength and individuality of people living with disability. Iâ€™m honoured that several of those photographs are now part of the exhibition Disability Through the Lens â€“ Our Life Stories, launched yesterday in Valletta, featuring work by Therese Debono, Matthew Mirabelli and RenÃ© Rossignaud.
Over the coming days Iâ€™ll be sharing some of these portraits and the stories behind them. If you can, visit the exhibition at Spazju Kreativ, Valletta, open until January 4 â€” take the time to look, reflect, listen and rethink.
First up: Annemarie & Matthew Bugeja.
Siblings full of determination, discipline and heart. I remember how many frames it took to get them perfectly in sync â€” none of us gave up, and eventually everything clicked.
Annemarie has represented Malta in multiple Special Olympics World Games â€” Athens 2011, Antwerp 2014, Los Angeles 2015, Abu Dhabi 2019, Berlin 2023 â€” winning Silver (Vault & Beam) and Bronze (Bars & All Around) in LA, with further medals in later editions. She holds a Bachelors (Hons) in Sports & Physical Fitness from MCAST and works as a primary teacher and coach.
Matthew, also born with hearing loss, channels his energy through sport â€” gymnastics, athletics and more recently football. He represented Malta in Athens 2011, Antwerp 2014, Los Angeles 2015 and Berlin 2023, winning Gold in Rings and Silver All-Around in LA, and Gold in the 200m in Berlin. He works with the Armed Forces of Malta.
A portrait of strength, family and possibility.

Officials badge from the 43rd, and last edition of the Peace race while under Communist control.
-
As the riders departed from Warsaw on the 8th May from within a fracturing Eastern Bloc, it was clear that the Communist run regimes were losing their grip in each of these countries.
-
As they rode through Czechoslovakia, in neighboring Hungary border guards had begun cutting down the barbed wire that marked their frontier with Austria and the West, allowing thousands to flee the Communist regime.
-
In Poland a huge series of labour strikes had forced the regime leaders to agree to round table talks with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, resulting in Poland holding its own semi-free elections that June.
-
By August the focus for change would then be the Czech capital Prague, where thousands began fleeing the city to the West by train, culminating in the â€˜Velvet Revolution, that would soon also bring Czech citizens their own free elections too.
-
As the last host country of the Peace Race, the German Democratic Republic, it too would soon have its own moment in history, one that would fittingly be focused on its capital East Berlinâ€¦
-
This series of protests in the GDR that eventually led to the fall of the Berlin Wall, and Communism, began in the city of Leipzig, where a peaceful march by 70,000 people shook the East German Communist regime to its core.
-
An event that left a lasting impression on the Commander of the Leipzig KGB headquarters on duty that evening, one Vladimir Putinâ€¦
-
And the rest as they say, is history.

Do you still live in Boston?

Iâ€™d be rich if i got a dollar for every time this question has been asked in the last decade. Maybe youâ€™ve noticed I get the travel bug sometimes. I really do love a good solo international trip (2016 Shangai/Hong Kong was my first) and I donâ€™t take for granted how difficult it is to remove your self from everything you know that brings you safety and comfort. Yes, Iâ€™m looking at you if youâ€™re a transplant to Boston. 

But letâ€™s keep it a buckâ€¦ traveling with friends is such a dope experience. Iâ€™ve long been in the season of combining a few things that bring me so much joy: travel, community, photography, and cycling. 

Colombia kicked my ass in many ways. It continued to teach me what brotherhood, communication, and respect looks like. It challenged my physical limits beyond what I thought I was capable of. It opened my eyes to the way capitalism continues to bring so much harm to us and people around the world. And it taught me that weâ€™re being kept from the embrace that so many cultures and experiences around the world are waiting to share with us.

The message is book that trip and allow yourself to be transformed. Side note: choose carefully because traveling while Black ainâ€™t easy.

GRWM with me. âœŒï¸ Last week being unemployed! âœ¨

â€œInstead of worrying about what you cannot control, shift your energy to what you can create.â€
â€•  Roy T. Bennett

Being in your laid-off phase makes it hard to keep balance. It's easy to fall in this pit of waking up late and look at job aggregation sites and be depressed for the rest of the week that yet again there's so little on the market. So this is my routine every Monday to start the week optimistically. âœŒï¸ 

This time it's a special episode for me. As this is my last week being unemployed! ğŸ¤©
Last week was quite crazy. I had a terrible cold, had a few job interviews and all of a sudden I heard back from a company who previously decided to move forward with someone else. They did let me know that it was an incredibly close call and they were willing to do me an offer as soon as a new position was available. Well, that position came sooner than I could've imagined. ğŸ˜‡ (I'll share more about it soon)

In the end last week's call of hoping the storm wouldn't be a sign of the week turned out to be the case anyway, but in a good way! Despite getting a bit sick and having a few interviews, I also got the very good news! âœ¨ Luckily there's always sunshine after the rain. ğŸ˜‰

With that, I can finally rest this week. Take some time to enjoy myself knowing there's light at the end of the tunnel. No more hunting, hoping for replies and feeling depressed seeing how little opportunities there are out there..

I know it's tough on the market right now. But I do want to emphasize how important it is to try and stay positive. Keep yourself going, do things you enjoy and keep you alive. It's the only way to get the most out of this situation we can't control. 

You got this! ğŸ«¶

And as always;
Happy coding everyone! ğŸ‘¨â€ğŸ’»

Math is the foundation of every video game ğŸ˜‰ (whether you use tools or not)

"Go down deep enough into anything and you will find mathematics."
â€” Dean Schlicter 

It keeps bothering me that some people like to say "we don't use math when making video games", "engines do all the math for us", "math is not essential to make games".. And yet many aspiring game developers quit because they think it's too heavy on mathematics.. ğŸ¤” (which is a shame)

I mean, just to render a pixel has math behind it. Why are you ignoring it? Rather just embrace it! ğŸ˜‰

Just like I say in this video; using matrices, quaternions, trigonometry, interpolations and random probabilities are a daily occurrence when making video games. Whether you use tools or not, the math is there. And to get the most out of it, a (at least basic) understanding of the math behind it will allow you to bring the best out of it. ğŸ™Œ

ğŸ’¡ But don't be afraid of math.
When I was in high school I found math very scary and boring. But now I realized I just didn't get it. Once I started to make video games I learned by doing. With making games you can literally see a mathematical failure (like a character being yeeted 1000 yards away ğŸ˜‰). It makes it fun and makes it super satisfying once you get the equation right. It makes you understand and see the beauty of it. At least, it did for me. ğŸ«¶

And I don't want to forget to mention that mathematical equations make more sense as well. Instead of having arbitrary names you can use actual references. Making an equation easier to understand. For example xi and xj become 'player.x' and 'target.x'. Making it easier to identify the number used (very basic example).

So, stop being afraid and stop ignoring the use of math in making video games. 
Embrace it! âœ¨

The thing about this Full Moon in Gemini is that it exposes the part of you that keeps asking for clarity while the world keeps throwing noise at your face. Folks are stretched thin right now and it is not just information overload. It is meaning starvation. When your mind gets flooded, your spirit starts yelling, and this lunation pulls that truth out of hiding.

Gemini lights up the loop. Sagittarius lights up the quest. Virgo tightens around control. Pisces softens you back into trust. And somewhere inside all that, your nervous system is trying to remember what your intuition sounds like without the static. That is the real crisis. Not just misinformation but the erosion of inner knowing.

This moon wants you to pause long enough to hear yourself again. The panic. The spiraling. The insomnia. The Nine of Swords moment is not doom. It is your body asking you to stop abandoning yourself. You have been carrying too much. You have been thinking for the entire world. You have been trying to make sense of chaos with a tired mind.

So use this lunation to slow down. Step away from the scroll. Anchor in one truth that feels like it belongs to you. Let your intuition guide you before the algorithm does. Say the scary thing out loud and watch it lose power. Create real silence so your inner voice can stretch out again.

Gemini shows you the pattern. Sagittarius points you toward meaning. Pisces restores trust. Virgo refines the path. When all four speak at once, you get a moment where clarity cuts through the fog and you remember you are not lost. You are overwhelmed.

This Full Moon is not here to frighten you. It is here to stop you from abandoning yourself in the whirlwind. It is here to remind you that your inner truth is still loud, still living, still reachable.

If you want your intuition to grow, you have to give it room to breathe.

Many autistic kids thrive on routines because routines make the world feel predictable and safe. When something happens once, like a trip to the store after school, their brain may treat it as a new pattern. Itâ€™s not stubbornness; itâ€™s how their nervous system creates order. Changes or â€œbreakingâ€ a routine can feel confusing or overwhelming, especially if theyâ€™ve already connected the activity with comfort, fun, or regulation. Thatâ€™s why even a simple grocery trip can quickly become an expected daily ritual. 

Predictability = less anxiety. 
Sudden change = uncertainty their brain isnâ€™t prepared for. 

Supporting flexibility is a skill that develops over time, and itâ€™s totally okay to gently guide them when something canâ€™t become a daily routine. Visuals, countdowns, or preparing them ahead of time (â€œNot today, but maybe Fridayâ€) can help ease the transition without causing distress. Roasted Cabbage (method)
â€¢Process cabbage and then oil and salt your portions. In a ripping hot pan, add your cabbage and sear hard until well caramelized. Add butter to your pan and base, making sure you lift the seared side of the cabbage to introduce butter there as well for further caramelization. Add thyme and allow it to bloom. Transfer to a 350 degree oven and cook until very tender (about 30 minutes). 
â€¢
Vegetable Jus
300g leeks
50g shallot 
100g garlic
â€¢In a pot, roast these ingredients well until caramelized.
100g butter
7 sprigs of fresh thyme
â€¢Add butter and stir while you allow it to foam and begin to brown, add thyme and allow to pop and stir until ultra fragrant.
200g cognac or fortified wine
100g molasses
50g brown sugar
1000g vegetable stock
25g salt (more to taste if needed as well as white vinegar)
â€¢Deglaze with your liquor and cook to au sec. Add your remaining ingredients and cook until your jus naturally thickens in to a beautifully syrupy and viscus pool of greatness. Strain and emulsify in a knob or two of butter to form a proper sauce.

	1. In a large pot, add the whole chicken, water, salt, ginger, green onion, and onion. Bring to a boil, then lower to a gentle simmer.
	2.	Simmer until the chicken is cooked through (about 45â€“60 minutes). Remove the chicken, shred the meat, and set aside. Strain and reserve the broth.
	3.	Toast the jasmine rice in a dry pan until fragrant. Add it to the reserved broth. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until the rice breaks down into a thick porridge (about 60â€“90 minutes). Add the chicken bouillon, fish sauce, and a dash of sugar. Adjust add salt and adjust as needed.
	4.	Ladle the congee into bowls, top with shredded chicken and your favorite toppings. (I did chillies, green onions, and fried shallots)
