Cucumber Kimchi ğŸ¥’ğŸŒ¶ï¸ Made using homegrown cucumbers for a little #gardentotable moment ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€ğŸŒ¾ğŸƒ I've been enjoying it with most of my dinners as the perfect little side dish - it's refreshing, crunchy and so flavourful! 

ğŸ‘‡ SAVE THIS RECIPEğŸ‘‡

Base:
3 medium cucumbers
1/2 - 1 tbsp coarse sea salt
2 stalks green onions, thinly sliced (or garlic chives if you have them!)
1 small carrot, thinly sliced or shredded

Paste:
2 tbsp gochugaru 
1/2 apple, grated (I like to use this instead of sugar, but you can sub with a few tsp sweetener)
1/4 brown onion, finely grated
1 tbsp vegan fish sauce
1 clove garlic, finely grated
1 tsp grated ginger

Method: 
1. Wash your cucumbers well, halve lengthways then thinly slice them on a slight angle. 
2. Transfer to a large bowl and sprinkle enough sea salt to coat all of the cucumber slices (I used just under 1 tbsp). Toss well and set aside for at least 15-20 minutes or until liquid has pooled to the bottom of the bowl. 
3. Discard the liquid, then rinse the cucumber a few times to get rid of any excess salt. I like to taste it just to be sure. Drain/dry well. 
4. In the meantime, add all of the paste ingredients into a bowl and mix well to combine. 
5. Add the cucumber, carrots and green onions to the paste and mix well until everything is evenly coated. 
6. Serve immediately or transfer into a container and store it in the fridge (I do this since I personally prefer fresh kimchi). If you want it to be more fermented and sour, leave at room temperature overnight or for 24 hours before storing in the fridge. Enjoy ğŸ’š

ğŸ”¥ The phone you cannot just buy ğŸ˜³ğŸ“±

The Samsung Galaxy Z Trifold is so exclusive in Singapore that you need a special invitation before you can even think about owning it. Money alone cannot save you here.

Super thin at 3.9 millimetres, basically the width of a USB C port, and the U shaped fold feels easy to handle. Try to close it the wrong way and it gives you a haptic warning, like a mini safety officer.

Folded, it is chunky at 309 grams, but still manageable. Open it up and that massive display is perfect for dramas, browsing and flipping orientation to read long documents comfortably.

There is one disappointment, no screen continuity. Apps must reload when you unfold, which really breaks the flow.

But for multitasking, the screen size is a dream. Split screen is fluid, DeX is built in, and wireless projection gives you another display if you want to go full mobile-workflow mode.

It is futuristic, niche and definitely a flex.
Would you buy it if Samsung invited you?

Why does freezing it bring the ink back? ğŸ¤”â„ï¸

The Pilot FriXion pen uses heat-sensitive ink that turns transparent when you rub it with the special eraser on the penâ€™s cap. The friction creates enough heat to trigger a chemical reaction that makes the ink invisible. Itâ€™s still there on the page, just transparent. Thatâ€™s why your notes can fade if you leave them in a hot car or direct sunlight. The cold reverses this reaction, so you can actually bring disappeared ink back by putting the page in the freezer.

Beyond the standard FriXion pens, Pilot makes several other products using this same technology. The FriXion Light Natural highlighters come in soft, muted colors that work well if you prefer subtle highlighting. The FriXion Stamps are designed for journaling and planners and they come in various designs, including some unexpected options. And the FriXion Ball Waai gel pens have pastel ink colors with the same heat-erasable properties.

All of these use that same thermochromic ink system, which makes them popular for anyone who wants to be able to correct mistakes or change their mind about highlighting without using correction tape or starting over.

Meet Bella, one of our sweet survivors ğŸ’—
She arrived here over the summer on a day that was already unbearably heavy. I had just gotten a call about an opossum mom and her babies in the road. The finder refused to move her, and by the time I reached them, it was too late. I drove away heartbroken, disappointed, and honestly questioning how people can walk away from animals who need help so desperately.

And thenâ€”another call came in.
A woman had just watched the car in front of her hit an opossum. Instead of driving off, she stopped, scooped the injured opossum out of the road, and immediately said she would drive two hours straight to us to get her help. Her compassion, her urgency, her genuine concernâ€¦ in that moment, my faith in humanity knitted itself back together a little.

That opossum was Bella. ğŸ¤

She arrived in rough shapeâ€”a badly broken leg, traumatic amputation of her tail, nystagmus from head trauma, among other issues â€”but we could see the spark in her. She spent eight full weeks on strict crate rest so her leg could heal. Her leg still flops out to the side and she wonâ€™t ever be releasable, but it doesnâ€™t cause her pain.

Now that sheâ€™s safe, Bella has fully embraced her well-earned retirement from the wild. As an older opossum, she is a very gentle soulâ€”grateful for her  cozy beds, every homemade meal, and especially her nightly runs on her wheel. She settles into her new life with such quiet sweetness that you canâ€™t help but adore her.

Thank you to everyone who stops, helps, cares, and chooses compassion. And to everyone who supports our mission- donors, volunteers, followers. You make stories like Bellaâ€™s possible â¤ï¸â€ğŸ©¹

Meet our newest critical intake â€” a gentle soul who has been struggling for far too long.
Heâ€™s absolutely emaciated, covered in fleas, mites, ticks, and burrs â€” all signs that heâ€™s been too unwell to groom himself. Heâ€™s extremely weak, but what concerns us most is a severe infection involving his eye and nasal region.

After getting subcutaneous fluids, antibiotics, eye medication, and pain management, we tucked him into a cozy bed in the incubator. You can see the relief in his body â€” he finally feels safe, warm, and cared for. He is the sweetest, most gentle boy, and weâ€™re giving him every chance to fight.

It took quite a relay team to get this precious opossum here. His wonderful finders spotted him struggling last night and acted immediately to safely contain him. They were two hours away, so I reached out to my dear friend and fellow rehabber Tina, who was able to take him in overnight. Then, through an incredible relay of transport volunteers, he made it to us early this morning.

A huge thank you to Tina, Paul, Jessica, Aryanna, and Liliana for all of your efforts to save this precious boy! 
Our transport team has grown so much over the last year, and because of them, weâ€™re able to save lives all over New York.

Weâ€™re doing everything we can for this little opossum. Please keep him in your thoughts â€” he has a long road ahead, but now he has a fighting chance. â¤ï¸ğŸƒ

Adoptable Animal Presented by Amazon: Emjay

Meet Emjay - Your 100-Pound Lap Dog with a Heart of Gold!

At 6.5 years old, Emjay is a gentle, soulful bulldog who's equal parts snuggly teddy bear and backyard goofball. He may tip the scales at nearly 100 pounds, but don't tell him that-he still firmly believes he's a lap dog. If you're looking for a cuddle companion who's always down for a nap on the couch (preferably with his head on your chest), Emjay might just be your guy.

Emjay lives for the little things in life: quiet walks, sniffing the breeze, and lazy afternoons spent lounging near his people. Due to some ongoing health concerns and his age, he's happiest in calm environments where he can take things at his own pace. That said, don't be fooled-he still gets spectacular bursts of playful energy and loves to show off his moves with his favorite toys in the backyard.

Emjay is working hard on his dog social skills and is making amazing progress! He's learning to check in with his handler when he spots another dog and is getting better at staying calm and focused. He'll thrive with adopters who can advocate for his space, especially in busy or dog-heavy environments. He's not asking for isolation-just a little understanding. To help him feel secure (and show off his impressive training chops), he wears his muzzle like a pro.

Smart as they come, Emjay picks up new cues quickly and is always eager to learn. He's already fluent in a variety of commands and is motivated by praise, treats, and the occasional silly voice.

Like all of us, Emjay carries some baggage, and he'll need a patient, loving home that's willing to work with him as he adjusts to his new life. But we promise-he's absolutely worth it. He's not just a dog; he's a loyal, expressive companion with so much love to give.

Email adoption@torontohumanesociety.com with the subject line "Emjay"
Visit us at 11 River Street to speak with an Adoption Agent and begin the adoption process.

Grizzly Bear vs. Black Wolf ğŸ’¥

This year I witnessed three separate instances of Grizzly Bears and Wolves compete for a food source. Here are some things I noticed:
1.) Both of these apex predators took plenty of time to asses the situation and their competition before making any drastic moves, showing the intellect and reasoning abilities of both of these animals. Risk vs Reward.
2.) It seems that grizzlies are the ones that control the situation and food source. Although, when the wolves were packed up, they were more likely to test the bear. 1 on 1, the bear was the dominant animal. (Iâ€™m sure there have been many instances of wolves running a grizzly off, Iâ€™m just noting my three experiences.)
3.) Wolves have a lot of patience. Even when their food was taken over by a grizzly, 2/3 times the wolves waited patiently nearby until the bear had its share and moved on.
4.) It seems they both would prefer to not get into a physical altercation. Their â€œfightsâ€ were more of a display of dominance rather than getting physical and inflicting injury on each other. I believe they recognize each other as apex predators and have a healthy respect for each other.

This video is from Hayden Valley when Grizzly Bear 791 and the Wapiti Lake Wolf Pack took turns on this bison over the course of several days. This was a very brave wolf! The only one that stood its ground when the grizzly stomped at it.

Tiger Hill Pagoda, located atop Tiger Hill in Suzhou, Jiangsu Province, is one of the iconic landmarks of the ancient city. Built in 959 AD (the sixth year of the Xiande era of the Later Zhou Dynasty) and completed in 961 AD (the second year of the Jianlong era of the Northern Song Dynasty), it boasts a history of over 1000 years. Tiger Hill Pagoda is one of the oldest existing brick-structured pagodas in Jiangnan and is hailed as "China's First Leaning Tower." Due to uneven foundation settlement, the pagoda has gradually tilted, with a maximum tilt angle of approximately 3Â°59â€². Although its tilt is less than that of the Leaning Tower of Pisa in Italy, it was built over 200 years earlier and is one of the world's most famous leaning towers. Tiger Hill Pagoda, along with Suzhou gardens, bridges, and flowing water, forms the cultural image of Suzhou and is known as "the most beautiful scenic spot in Wuzhong." Literary figures throughout history, such as Bai Juyi and Su Shi, have visited and composed poems about it. Su Shi's famous saying, "To visit Suzhou without seeing Tiger Hill is a great regret," is widely known. Tiger Hill Pagoda is not only an architectural marvel but also a testament to Suzhou's millennium-long history. Its unique tilted shape, precious cultural relics, and landscape that blends nature and culture make it an indispensable symbol of Jiangnan culture.

Tips for a better deadliftâ€¦

1. Set Your Feet Right

Conventional: hip-width apart, toes slightly out.
Sumo: wide stance, feet angled 30â€“45Â°.
âœ” Stable feet = stable pull.

2. Lock Your Lats In

Think:
	â€¢	â€œSqueeze oranges in your armpits.â€
	â€¢	â€œPut your shoulder blades in your back pockets.â€

This keeps the bar close and prevents rounding.

3. Bar Over Midfoot

Before you grab the bar, look down:
The bar should be directly over your midfootâ€”not your toes.
This is one of the biggest fixes for balance + power.

4. Hips in the Right Spot

Not too high (becomes an RDL), not too low (turns into a squat).
Your hips should allow your shins to lightly touch the bar when you drop down to grab it.

5. Brace Like Youâ€™re About to Get Punched

Take a big breath into your belly, not your chest.
Lock your core before you pull.
A strong brace = straight spine and more power.

6. Pull Slack Out of the Bar

Before actually lifting, apply tension:
	â€¢	Slightly pull up
	â€¢	Feel the plates â€œclickâ€ or tension the bar

This puts you in a tight, explosive starting position.

7. Keep the Bar Glued to You

The bar should drag up your shins and thighs.
If it swings forward, the lift gets instantly harder.

8. Push the Floor Away

Instead of â€œyankingâ€ the bar, think leg drive:
â€œPush the floor away through your heels.â€
This prevents jerking and keeps hips/shoulders rising together.

9. Hips + Shoulders Move Together First

If your hips shoot up first, your form is breaking.
If your chest rises too early, youâ€™re squatting the weight.
Both should lift at the same time for the first few inches.

10. Finish by Squeezing, Not Leaning

Lock out by squeezing your glutes.
Donâ€™t hyperextend your lower back at the top.

Kepala BNPB Letjen TNI Suharyanto menyampaikan permohonan maaf kepada seluruh masyarakat Indonesia. Permohonan maaf ini terkait pernyataannya viral soal 'banjir Sumatera hanya ramai di media sosial'.

"Saya menyesal dan meminta maaf, pernyataan saya secara lengkap sebetulnya tadinya hanya berkaitan dengan kondisi Tapanuli Utara yang saat saya datang sejak hari pertama bencana di lapangan untuk Tarutung, Silangit dan sekitarnya tidak separah Tapanuli Tengah dan Sibolga, untuk menenangkan masyarakat di sana, tapi redaksinya keliru, saya siap salah," kata Suharyanto.

Eks Pangdam V/Brawijaya ini menegaskan, penjelasannya bukan untuk membela diri. Dari lubuk hati paling dalam, ia memastikan tidak pernah ada niatan meremehkan bencana yang terjadi di Sumatera.

"Saya tidak membela diri tapi demi Allah tidak sedikitpun di hati, pikiran dan tindakan saya yang meremehkan bencana ini, sejak awal saya tidak keluar dari 3 provinsi ini, dan mengerahkan kekuatan penuh BNPB baik personel, materiil dan segala sumber daya yang dimiliki," ucap Suharyanto.

While attending the 2025 North American Mayors Summit Against Antisemitism in New Orleans on Wednesday, Mayor Eric Adams announced an executive order than bars New York City from divesting from Israel, or from following business moves laid out by the BDS (boycott, divestment and sanctions) movement for Palestinian rights.

"Executive Order 60 makes it clear: BDS has no place in our city," Adams wrote on social media. "The movement is antisemitic in nature and discriminatory in practice. NYC contracts and pensions must serve the public good. Discrimination is illegal. Antisemitism is abhorrent."

The move directly challenges Mayor-elect Zohran Mamdani, who has said he is pro-BDS practices, as discussed in a sit-down interview with 1010 WINS just before his election.

"I've said that I don't believe that we should be purchasing Israel bonds, and that we should continue the practice of the current comptroller, who allowed those bonds to lapse," Mamdani told 1010 WINS' Susan Richard in October.
